Modbus Master
\layout Standard

The modbus master can use serial or ethernet ports.
 Modbus master is a userspace program so it might have latency issues on
 a heavily loaded computer.
 The ClassicLadder GUI must be running for Modbus to be running.
 Modbus is not fully finished so it does not do all modbus functions.
 To get modbus to initialize you must load a configure file when loading
 the ClassicLadder user space program eg.
 loadusr -w classicladder myprogram.clp --config=modbusfile (assuming modbusfile
 and myprogram.clp are present -w makes HAL wait till you close classicladder
 before closing realtime session) As it stands now ClassicLadder also loads
 a TCP modbus slave (if you load a config file) - I have not tested this
 nor have I tested the TCP modbus master.
 Modbus function 2,3,4,5,6,8,15,16 (read inputs, read holding registers,
 read input registers, write single coils, write single register, echo test,
 write multiple coils, write multiply registers) are currently available.
 If you do not specify a config file when loading the ClassicLadder user
 program this (next) page will not be displayed.
 [show config window]
\layout Standard

SERIAL PORT - For IP -blank - For serial - the location/name of serial driver
 eg.
 /dev/ttyS0 SERIAL SPEED - Should be set to speed the slave is set for PAUSE
 INTER-FRAME - Pause between requests DEBUG LEVEL Set this to 0-3 (0 to
 stop printing debug info besides no-response errors).
 SLAVE ADDRESS - For serial-The slaves ID number usually settable on the
 slave device (usually 1-256) - For IP -The slave IP address plus optionally
 the port number.
 TYPE ACCESS - Inputs are input bits (%I), coils are output bits (%Q), holding
 registers/writing registers are %W words 1st MODBUS ELEMENT - The address
 (or register number) of the first element in a group.
 NUMBER OF ELEMENTS - The number of elements in this group LOGIC - You can
 invert the logic here 1st%I%Q MAPPED - This is the starting number of %I,
 %Q, or %W variables that are mapped on to the modbus element group (starting
 at the first modbus element number)
\layout Standard

In the example above: Port number- for my computer /dev/ttyS0 was my serial
 port The serial speed is set to 9600 baud.
 Slave address is set to 12 ( on my VFD I can set this from 1-31, meaning
 I can talk to 31 VFDs maximum on one system) The first line is set up for
 8 input bits starting at the first register number (register 1) so register
 numbers 1-8 and maps them on to Classicladder's %I variables starting at
 %I1 ending at %I8.
 The second line is set for 2 output bits starting at the ninth register
 number (register 9) so register numbers 9-10 and maps them on to ClassicLadder'
s %Q variables starting at %Q9 ending at %Q10.
 The third line is set to write 2 registers (16 bit each) starting at the
 0 ith register number (register 0) so register numbers 0-1 and maps them
 on to ClassicLadder's %W variables starting at %W0 ending at %W1 (which
 could be memory or s32 in/out HAL pins depending on what objects you loaded
 in ClassicLadder real time ).
 It's easy to make an off-by-one error as sometimes the modbus elements
 are referenced starting at one rather then 0 (actually by the standard
 that is the way it's supposed to be!).
 The documents for your modbus slave device will tell you how the registers
 are set up- there is no standard way.
 The SERIAL PORT, PORT SPEED, PAUSE, and DEBUG level are editable for experiment
al changes (when you close the config window values are written) but will
 not be saved when you save a ladder program-you'll have to edit the config
 file.
